<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Jones, John. Letter to Judge Adam Mabane, 1787, with a copy of Jones's testimony 1783. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0003</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p style="text-align:justify;">Man; if I suffer them to pass without Contradiction they will be taken for proved; a Man under so foul a Stigma is incapable of enjoying the rights of Society, <span class="DelHand-author">and</span> <span class="AddHand-author">he </span>is disqualified to act as a Citizen.  I am <span class="AddHand-author">on </span>this day discharging the Duty of a Grand Juror, a Duty which the Constitution <span class="DelHand-author">of</span> <span class="AddHand-author">&amp;</span> Laws of my Country teach me to be of a very serious and important Nature; If your accusation is <span class="DelHand-author">fact</span> <span class="AddHand-author">just</span>, I am henceforth neither Competent to be a Juror, nor to be received as a Witness in any Court of Justice; and thus you have discribed me as an Exile by the Law, the out-cast of Society; Injured as I am, and feeling as I do, I should be justified if I dipt my pen in Gall.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">It would seem that your invective and declamation cost you little pains, they have flowed freely from a rich fountain; and tho' they will not be received for truth by dispassionate men, it is necessary that I make my defence public, as you have your Comments <span class="AddHand-author">to prevent any improper impressions being fixt on the minds of my fellows citizens.</span>  I address myself to you, because in the Language I discover the <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Man</span>: I shall not imitate your example; I shall convey my justification in terms of Decency and Respect.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">You have had the confidence to Charge me with <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Temerity</span> &amp; <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Untruth</span>, and to assert</p>
